SIMPLE: odious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Odious
<hw>O"di*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>odiosus</ets>, from <ets>odium</ets> hatred: cf. F.
<ets>odieux</ets>. See <er>Odium</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Hateful;
deserving or receiving hatred; <as>as, an <ex>odious</ex> name, system,
vice</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All wickedness will be most
<xex>odious</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sprat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He rendered himself <qex>odious</qex> to the Parliament.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Causing or provoking hatred, repugnance, or disgust;
offensive; disagreeable; repulsive; <as>as, an <ex>odious</ex> sight; an
<ex>odious</ex> smell.</as></def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>odious</qex> side of that polity.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hateful; detestable; abominable; disgusting;
loathsome; invidious; repulsive; forbidding; unpopular.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>O"di*ous`ly</wf>. <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>O"di*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Odist</ent>⟦br⟧
